[[File:Old and new London - a narrative of its history, its people, and its places (1873) (14761544406).jpg|thumb|The frost fair of 1683-84]]
The '''Great Frost of 1683–84''' was a [[frost]] across [[England]], reported as the worst in its history.<ref name="The Independent - 17 November 2013 - The 10 worst British winters ever - 1. The winter of 1684">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/the-10-worst-british-winters-ever-8945584.html?action=gallery&ino=10|title=The 10 worst British winters ever - 1. The winter of 1684|last=Williams|first=Rob|date=17 November 2013|work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref>  During the Frost, the surface of the [[River Thames]] was reported as frozen to the depth of one [[Foot (unit)|foot]].<ref name="The Guardian - 15 May 2010 - Great dynasties of the world: The Chipperfields">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/may/15/chipperfields-circus-family-dynasties|title=Great dynasties of the world: The Chipperfields|last=[[Ian Sansom]]|date=15 May 2010|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref> The Great Frost enabled the first [[River Thames frost fairs|River Thames frost fair]].<ref name="The Independent - 17 November 2013 - The 10 worst British winters ever - 1. The winter of 1684"/> Entertainment on the frozen Thames as result of the Great Frost began the career of [[Chipperfield's Circus]].<ref name="The Guardian - 15 May 2010 - Great dynasties of the world: The Chipperfields"/>  A Great Frost Fair was also held in [[Leeds]], when the [[River Aire]] froze solid for a month allowing a fair with an ox-roast and sports to take place, as described by [[Ralph Thoresby]].<ref name=Mitchell>{{cite book |last=Mitchell |first= W. R. |date=2000 |title=A History of Leeds |url= |location=Chichester |publisher=Phillimore |page=52 |isbn=1 86077 130 0|author-link= }}</ref>

