{{Hatnote|For the events in New York City, see [[Central Park be-in]].}} [[Image:Humanbein-p.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Poster advertising the 'Human Be-In' designed by [[Stanley Mouse]](artist), [[Michael Bowen (artist)|Michael Bowen]](concept) using the photograph of artist Casey Sonnabend.]]
The '''Human Be-In''' was an event in [[San Francisco]]'s [[Golden Gate Park]] Polo Fields on January&nbsp;14,&nbsp;1967.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/love/program/love_02_wm_lo.html|title=American Experience Summer of Love|publisher=PBS}}</ref> It was a prelude to San Francisco's [[Summer of Love]], which made the [[Haight-Ashbury]] district a symbol of American [[counterculture]] and introduced the word "[[wikt:psychedelic|psychedelic]]" to [[suburbia]].
==Origins==
The Human Be-In focused the key ideas of the [[1960s counterculture]]: personal empowerment, cultural and political decentralization, [[commune (intentional community)|communal living]], [[Ecology|ecological]] awareness, [[higher consciousness]] (with the aid of psychedelic drugs), acceptance of illicit psychedelics use, and radical [[Liberalism|liberal]] [[political consciousness]].<ref name="Powis2003">{{cite web|url=http://www.radionetherlands.nl/features/cultureandhistory/031221be-in.html |publisher=Radio Netherlands Worldwide |first=Neville |last=Powis |title=The Human Be-In and the Hippy Revolution |date=22 January 2003 |access-date=21 April 2006 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060421102203/http://www.radionetherlands.nl/features/cultureandhistory/031221be-in.html |archivedate=21 April 2006 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.org/thisday/jan14/human-be-/|title=Human Be-In|last=Society|first=National Geographic|date=2014-12-12|work=National Geographic Society|access-date=2017-08-17|language=en}}</ref> The [[Hippies|hippie movement]] developed out of disaffected student communities around [[San Francisco State University]], [[City College of San Francisco|City College]] and [[University of California, Berkeley|Berkeley]] and in San Francisco's [[beat generation]] poets and jazz [[Hipster (1940s subculture)|hipsters]], who also combined a search for intuitive spontaneity with a rejection of "[[middle-class]] [[morality]]". [[Allen Ginsberg]] personified the transition between the beat and hippie generations.
The Human Be-In took its name from a chance remark by the artist [[Michael Bowen (artist)|Michael Bowen]] made at the [[Love Pageant Rally]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfbg.com/entry.php?entry_id=4344&catid=4&volume_id=254&issue_id=311&volume_num=41&issue_num=47|title=San Francisco Bay Guardian|work=sfbg.com}}</ref> The playful name combined [[Humanism|humanist]] values with the scores of [[sit-in]]s that had been reforming college and university practices and eroding the vestiges of entrenched [[Racial segregation|segregation]], starting with the lunch counter sit-ins of 1960 in [[Greensboro sit-ins|Greensboro, North Carolina]], and [[Nashville sit-ins|Nashville, Tennessee]]. The first major [[teach-in]] had been organized by [[Students for a Democratic Society (1960 organization)|Students for a Democratic Society]] at the [[University of Michigan]], 24–25 March 1965.<ref>''New York Times'' 3/25/65.</ref>
==Event== The Human Be-In was announced on the cover of the fifth issue of the ''[[San Francisco Oracle]]'' as "A Gathering of the Tribes for a Human Be-In". The occasion was a new California law banning the use of the psychedelic drug [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|LSD]] that had come into effect on October&nbsp;6,&nbsp;1966.<ref name = "Powis2003" /> The speakers at the rally were all invited by Bowen, the main organizer. They included [[Timothy Leary]] in his first San Francisco appearance, who set the tone that afternoon with his famous phrase "[[Turn on, tune in, drop out]]"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sfchronicle.com/music/article/Reliving-the-Human-Be-In-50-years-later-10854785.php#photo-12168922|title=Reliving the Human Be-In 50 years later|work=San Francisco Chronicle|access-date=2017-08-17}}</ref> and Richard Alpert (soon to be known as "[[Ram Dass]]"), and poets like [[Allen Ginsberg]], who chanted [[mantra]]s, [[Gary Snyder]] and Michael McClure. Other counterculture gurus included comedian [[Dick Gregory]], [[Lenore Kandel]], [[Lawrence Ferlinghetti]], [[Jerry Rubin]], and [[Alan Watts]]. The [[Hells Angels]], at the peak of their "outlaw" reputation, corralled lost children. Music was provided by a host of local [[rock band]]s including [[Jefferson Airplane]], [[The Grateful Dead]], [[Big Brother and the Holding Company]], [[Quicksilver Messenger Service]], and [[Blue Cheer]] most of whom had been staples of [[the Fillmore]] and the [[Avalon Ballroom]].<ref name = "Miles2004">{{cite book | title = Hippie | first = Barry | last = Miles | author-link = Barry Miles | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=fLulFlbAJGgC&dq | date = 2004 | publisher = Sterling | isbn = 978-1-40271-442-9}}</ref>{{rp|186-191}} "Underground chemist" [[Owsley Stanley]] provided massive amounts of his "White Lightning" LSD, specially produced for the event, as well as 75 twenty-pound turkeys, for free distribution by the [[Diggers (theater)|Diggers]].<ref name = Ringolevio>{{cite book | last = Grogan | first = Emmett | title = Ringolevio: A Life Played for Keeps | publisher = Citadel Press | year = 1990 | url = http://www.diggers.org/ringolevio.htm | isbn = 0-8065-1168-0 }}</ref>{{rp|267}}{{efn|[[Ringolevio]] p.274 - The turkeys had been made into thousands of sandwiches under John-John's supervision, and the bread was salted down with crushed acid. Gary organized the free distribution of the sandwiches to those who looked like they needed something to eat, physically or spiritually.}}
The national media were stunned, publicity about this event leading to the mass movement of young people from all over America to descend on the [[Haight-Ashbury]] area.<ref>{{cite book | title = Grassroots Medicine: The Story of America's Free Health Clinics | first = Gregory L. | last = Weiss | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=3NPaH01h0vYC&lpg=PP1&pg=PA29#v=onepage&q&f=false | date = 2006 | publisher = Rowman & Littlefield | isbn = 978-0-74254-070-5}}</ref> Reports were unable to agree whether 20,000<ref name = "Powis2003" /> or 30,000 people showed up at the Be-In.<ref name = "Miles2004" />{{rp|188}} Soon every gathering was an "-In" of some kind: Just 4 weeks later was [[Bob Fass]]'s [[Bob Fass#Human Fly-In|Human Fly-In]], then the [[Emmett Grogan]] inspired [[Bob Fass#Sweep In|Sweep-In]], Rowan and Martin's ''[[Laugh-In]]'' comedy television show began airing over [[NBC]] just a year later on January 22, 1968. This was followed by the first "[[Bob Fass#Yip In at Grand Central|Yip-In]]" (March 21, 1968, at [[Grand Central Terminal]]), "[[Love-in|Love-In]]" (April 14, 1968, at Malibu Canyon) and "[[Bed-In]]" (March 25, 1969, in Amsterdam).
The Human Be-In was later recalled by poet [[Allen Cohen (poet)|Allen Cohen]] (who assisted the artist Bowen in the organizational work,<ref>{{cite book | title = The Portable Sixties Reader | first = Ann | last = Charters | publisher = Penguin Classics | date = 2003 | isbn = 978-0-14-200194-3 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=i05HZYZjTuUC&pg=PA297 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Brugman | first = Bruce | title = Tonight: The Human Be-In 2007 | url = http://www.sfbg.com/blogs/bruce/2007/08/the_human_bein_jan_l4_l967_to.html }}</ref>) as a meld that brought together philosophically opposed factions of the San Francisco-based counterculture at the time: on one side, the Berkeley radicals, who were tending toward increased militancy in response to the [[Federal government of the United States|U.S.&nbsp;government]]'s [[Vietnam war]] policies, and, on the other side, the rather non-political Haight-Ashbury hippies, who urged peaceful protest. Their means were drastically different, but they held many of the same goals.<ref name="BB73">{{cite web | url = http://voices.revealdigital.com/cgi-bin/independentvoices?a=d&d=BFBJFGD19670106&e=-------en-20--1--txt-txIN---------------1 | title = Berkeley Barb, (Issue 73) | date = 6 January 1967 | website = Independent Voices: An Open Access collection of an Alternative Press | access-date = 13 January 2017 }}</ref>{{efn|[[Berkeley Barb]], (Issue 73) - Berkeley political activists are going to join San Francisco’s hippies in a love feast that will, hopefully, wipe out the last remnants of mutual skepticism and suspicion... In homes on both sides of the Bay while this was being shaped from a dream to a reality, the basic problem was whether to play the word game. The San Franciscans didn’t want to play that game any more; it doesn’t work, they said, and the non-verbal modes of expression tell it where it’s at. The Berkeleyans wanted to play that game because that’s where the rest of society plays; that’s the only way, they said, to get through to most people. The hip wondered aloud whether the politicos would make the Gathering a haranguing rally. The politicos wondered aloud whether the hip would all happily turn on and any social message would be lost. They solved it.}}
According to Cohen's own account,<ref name="cohen">Cohen, Allen [http://s91990482.onlinehome.us/allencohen/be-in.html "About the Human Be-In"] Note: has links to scans of organizational letters that Cohen wrote. This articles is also quoted by Bruce Brugman, online: [http://www.sfbg.com/blogs/bruce/2007/08/the_human_bein_jan_l4_l967_to.html]</ref> his friend Bowen provided much of the "organizing energy" for the event, and Bowen's personal connections also strongly influenced its character.<ref>As Allen Cohen put it: "he was friends with the Beat poets from the North Beach era, and had spent time with Tim Leary at Millbrook. He was an egocentric hustler who Allen Ginsberg had called the most convincing man he had ever known. He could charm the press and turn on a square. He credits himself for inviting Leary and the Beat poets to the Human Be-In, and arranging for it to be a worldwide media event."</ref>
The counterculture that surfaced at the "Human Be-In" encouraged people to "question authority" with regard to [[civil rights]], [[women's rights]], and [[consumer rights]]. Underground newspapers and radio stations served as its [[alternative media]].<ref name="BB73" />{{efn|[[Berkeley Barb]], (Issue 73) - The two radical scenes are for the first time beginning to look at each other more closely. What both see is that both are under a big impersonal stick called The Establishment. So they’re going to stand up together in what both hope to be a new and strong harmony.}}
== Influence == The Be-In later spawned a series of [[Digital Be-In]]s.
A UK&nbsp;theatre company, Theatre&nbsp;14167, (also 14167 films) takes its name from the date of the Be-In; the company subsequently produced work by [[Michael McClure]], who read at the event.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=SJgrAQAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22Theatre+14167%22 Theatre Record - Page 846, 2006]</ref>
