{{Infobox person | name = Joseph Hazelton | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = Joseph H. Hazelton | birth_date = 1853 | birth_place = [[Wilmington, New York|Wilmington]], [[Essex County, New York|Essex County]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1936|10|06|1853}} | death_place = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S. | occupation = Actor }}
'''Joseph H. Hazelton''' (ca. 1853 &ndash; October 8, 1936), aka '''Joseph Hazleton''', was an American stage and film actor. He appeared in 30 films between 1912 and 1922. As a boy program giver at [[Ford's Theatre]], he witnessed the [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|assassination]] of U.S. President [[Abraham Lincoln]] on April 14, 1865.
In 1933, Hazelton gave a lecture at [[May Company California|May Company]] Exposition Hall in Los Angeles and talked about watching Booth shoot Lincoln.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/373690/listen-to-a-rare-recording-of-an-eyewitness-account-of-lincolns-assassination/|title=Listen to a Rare Recording of an Eyewitness Account of Lincoln’s Assassination|author=|date=May 3, 2017|publisher=Hyperallergic Media}}</ref> An article in ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'' in its February 1927 edition, titled "This Man Saw Lincoln Shot," was the basis for a leaflet that Hazleton released to raise funds later in his life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lincolncollection.org/collection/creator-author/item/?cs=h&creator=Hazleton,+Joseph+H.,&item=100405|title=The assassination of President Lincoln / - The Lincoln Financial Foundation Collection|author=Joseph H. Hazelton|date=|website=www.lincolncollection.org}}</ref>
Hazelton died in [[Los Angeles, California]].
