{{otherpeople5|Agrippa (disambiguation)}}

'''Marcius Agrippa''' ([[floruit|fl.]] late 2nd/early 3rd century) was originally a slave serving as a [[beautician]]. He later became a [[freedman]] in some unknown way and then (illegally) started to encroach upon the rank of [[Equestrian (Roman)|Equestrian]], serving as ''advocatus fisci'' (an important official of the imperial treasury) during the reign of [[Septimius Severus]].  His impersonation of a man of higher rank was discovered shortly afterwards, and the emperor exiled him to an island.  He was called back to Rome by the emperor [[Caracalla]], probably given a grant of ''[[ingenui]]tas'', (i.e., an official declaration that he had the rights and legal status of one who had been born free) and he was elevated to [[Roman Senate|senator]]ial rank.<ref>{{cite book  | last = Reinhold  | first = Meyer  | |author2=[[American Philological Association]]   | title = Studies in Classical History and Society  | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]]  | date = 2002  | location = Oxford  | pages = 34  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=NbM3Ghoo3soC | isbn = 0-19-514543-7}}</ref>  He was appointed by the emperor [[Macrinus]] in 217, first to the government of [[Pannonia]] and afterwards to that of [[Dacia]].<ref>[[Cassius Dio]], lxxix. 13</ref><ref name="DGRBM">{{Cite book  | last = Smith  | first = William Smith  | author-link = William Smith (lexicographer)  | contribution = Agrippa, Marcius  | editor-last = Smith  | editor-first = William  | title = [[Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology]]  | volume = 1  | pages = 78  | publisher = [[Little, Brown and Company]]  | place = Boston  | year = 1867  | contribution-url = http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/0087.html }}</ref>

Agrippa is almost certainly the same person as the Marcius Agrippa, Roman admiral (likely of the [[classis Misenensis|Misenum fleet]]),<ref>{{cite book  | last = Botsford  | first = George Willis  | title = The Development of the Athenian Constitution  | publisher = [[Cornell University Press]]  | date = 1941  | location = Ithaca  | pages = 192  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=lpQLAAAAIAAJ  | isbn = 0-8371-7918-1}}</ref> who is mentioned by [[Augustan History|the Augustan histories]] "as privy to the death of [[Caracalla|Antoninus Caracallus]]."<ref>[[Spartianus]], ''Anton. Car.'' 6</ref>

