{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2011}} {{World-Scrabble-Championship | year=2003 | date-from=21 October 2003 | date-to=24 October 2003| location=[[Kuala Lumpur]] | winner=Panupol Sujjayakorn | number-of-players=90 | sponsor=Mattel | next=2005 | previous=2001 }}
The '''World Scrabble Championship 2003''' was held in the [http://www.corushotelkl.com/ Corus Hotel], [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]]. The winner was Panupol Sujjayakorn of [[Thailand]].<ref name=wsc2003>http://www.wscgames.com/2003/prizes.html</ref>
The format was notably different from previous [[World Scrabble Championship|WSCs]]. The tournament began with the [[Swiss_system_tournament#Scrabble|Australian Draw]] system, with each player playing sixteen games over two days. On the third day the players played eight games in a [[Swiss_system_tournament#Scrabble|King Of the Hill]] format. After this, the top two players competed in a best-of-five final to decide who would be the seventh World Scrabble Champion.
Prize money started at $17,500 for the winner, with all the top twenty players receiving prizes down to $200.
==Results==
The winner was [[Panupol Sujjayakorn]] of [[Thailand]]. This was the first time that a player won the WSC while representing a country for which [[English language|English]] is not the first language.
